ðŸ“— Poisson Distribution

 ðŸ”¹ Definition

The Poisson Distribution gives the probability of a given number of events happening in a fixed interval of time or space if these events occur with a known constant rate and independently of the time since the last event.

 ðŸ”¹ Probability Mass Function (PMF)

[
P(X = k) = \frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^k}{k!}
]

| Symbol      | Meaning                                      |
| :---------- | :------------------------------------------- |
| ( k )       | Number of occurrences                        |
| ( \lambda ) | Mean number of occurrences in given interval |
| ( e )       | Eulerâ€™s number (â‰ˆ 2.71828)                   |

 ðŸ”¹ Mean, Median, Mode, Variance

| Measure          | Formula                                                             |
| :--------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Mean             | ( \mu = \lambda )                                                   |
| Variance         | ( \sigma^2 = \lambda )                                              |
| Mode             | ( \lfloor \lambda \rfloor \text{ or } \lfloor \lambda \rfloor - 1 ) |
| Median (approx.) | ( \text{Median} \approx \lambda + 1/3 - 0.02/\lambda )              |

 ðŸ”¹ Example

If a call center receives an average of 4 calls per minute, find the probability of receiving exactly 2 calls in one minute.

[
P(X = 2) = \frac{e^{-4} \cdot 4^2}{2!} = \frac{0.0183 \cdot 16}{2} = 0.1464
]

ðŸ”¹ Key Properties

* Used for **counting events** in time or space.
* Mean = Variance = Î».
* Limiting case of Binomial Distribution when ( n \to \infty ), ( p \to 0 ), but ( n p = \lambda ).

